('chunk_685318ea41b332e835','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Adaptations of the trachea','**Definition.** The **trachea (windpipe)** is adapted to keep the airway open and clean: **C-shaped rings of cartilage** hold it open (prevent collapse when breathing); **ciliated cells** (tiny hairs) sweep mucus and trapped dust/germs upward; **mucus** (from goblet cells) traps particles.

**Real-world example.** Dust breathed in is caught in mucus and swept up by cilia to be swallowed or coughed out.

**Analogy.** The trachea is like a flexible vacuum hose: rings stop it collapsing, and a moving "conveyor belt" of cilia and mucus carries dirt away.

**Why it matters.** These adaptations protect the lungs from blockage and infection.

**Misconception.** *"Cartilage rings are complete circles."* Wrong — they are **C-shaped** (incomplete) so the oesophagus behind can expand when swallowing.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **State** two adaptations of the trachea.
- *(Apply)* **Explain** the role of cilia and mucus in the trachea.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why the cartilage rings are C-shaped rather than complete.

---','{"concept":1,"adaptations":3,"the":10,"trachea":5,"definition":1,"windpipe":1,"adapted":1,"keep":1,"airway":1,"open":2,"and":7,"clean":1,"shaped":3,"rings":4,"cartilage":3,"hold":1,"prevent":1,"collapse":1,"when":2,"breathing":1,"ciliated":1,"cells":2,"tiny":1,"hairs":1,"sweep":1,"mucus":5,"trapped":1,"dust":2,"germs":1,"upward":1,"from":2,"goblet":1,"traps":1,"particles":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"breathed":1,"caught":1,"swept":1,"cilia":3,"swallowed":1,"coughed":1,"out":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"flexible":1,"vacuum":1,"hose":1,"stop":1,"collapsing":1,"moving":1,"conveyor":1,"belt":1,"carries":1,"dirt":1,"away":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"these":1,"protect":1,"lungs":1,"blockage":1,"infection":1,"misconception":1,"are":3,"complete":2,"circles":1,"wrong":1,"they":1,"incomplete":1,"oesophagus":1,"behind":1,"can":1,"expand":1,"swallowing":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"two":1,"apply":1,"explain":2,"role":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"rather":1,"than":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_1486566b52431b6305','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Effects of smoking','**Definition.** **Smoking** harms the respiratory system. Effects include: **tar** paralysing/destroying cilia (so mucus and germs build up → "smoker''s cough", bronchitis); damage to alveoli causing **emphysema** (reduced surface area, breathlessness); **carbon monoxide** reducing the blood''s oxygen-carrying ability; **nicotine** addiction; and increased risk of **lung cancer**.

**Real-world example.** Long-term smokers often develop a chronic cough and shortness of breath due to damaged cilia and alveoli.

**Analogy.** Tar clogging the cilia is like gumming up a conveyor belt — dirt can no longer be cleared, so it piles up.

**Why it matters.** Links lifestyle choices to health; strong Criterion D discussion on personal freedom vs. public health.

**Misconception.** *"Only the smoker is harmed."* Wrong — **second-hand smoke** harms non-smokers nearby, especially children.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **List** three health effects of smoking on the respiratory system.
- *(Apply)* **Explain** how tar leads to a smoker''s cough.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Discuss** whether smoking should be banned in all public places.

---','{"concept":1,"effects":3,"smoking":4,"definition":1,"harms":2,"the":5,"respiratory":2,"system":2,"include":1,"tar":3,"paralysing":1,"destroying":1,"cilia":3,"mucus":1,"and":4,"germs":1,"build":1,"smoker":3,"cough":3,"bronchitis":1,"damage":1,"alveoli":2,"causing":1,"emphysema":1,"reduced":1,"surface":1,"area":1,"breathlessness":1,"carbon":1,"monoxide":1,"reducing":1,"blood":1,"oxygen":1,"carrying":1,"ability":1,"nicotine":1,"addiction":1,"increased":1,"risk":1,"lung":1,"cancer":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"long":1,"term":2,"smokers":2,"often":1,"develop":1,"chronic":1,"shortness":1,"breath":1,"due":1,"damaged":1,"analogy":1,"clogging":1,"like":1,"gumming":1,"conveyor":1,"belt":1,"dirt":1,"can":1,"longer":1,"cleared":1,"piles":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"links":1,"lifestyle":1,"choices":1,"health":3,"strong":1,"criterion":1,"discussion":1,"personal":1,"freedom":1,"public":2,"misconception":1,"only":1,"harmed":1,"wrong":1,"second":1,"hand":1,"smoke":1,"non":1,"nearby":1,"especially":1,"children":1,"command":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"list":1,"three":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"how":1,"leads":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"discuss":1,"whether":1,"should":1,"banned":1,"all":1,"places":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_06917d9cd3eb0b4a4d','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: The skeletal system and movement','**Definition.** The **skeleton** supports the body, protects organs, allows movement, and makes blood cells. Major bones include the **skull** (protects brain), **ribs** (protect heart/lungs), **spine/vertebrae** (support, protect spinal cord), **femur** (thigh — largest bone), **humerus** (upper arm), **pelvis**.

Movement needs **bones, muscles, tendons and ligaments** working together: **muscles** contract to pull bones; **tendons** attach muscle to bone; **ligaments** attach bone to bone at joints. Muscles work in **antagonistic pairs** (e.g. biceps and triceps) — one contracts while the other relaxes.

**Verbal diagram.** At the elbow: the biceps (front) attaches by a tendon across the joint; when it contracts it bends the arm, while the triceps (back) relaxes; to straighten, the triceps contracts and biceps relaxes.

**Real-world example.** Lifting a bag: the biceps contracts (pulling the forearm up); lowering it, the triceps contracts.

**Analogy.** Muscles and bones are like ropes and levers — muscles (ropes) pull on bones (levers) that pivot at joints.

**Why it matters.** Explains how the body moves and why muscles must work in pairs (they can only pull, not push).

**Misconception.** *"Muscles can push bones as well as pull."* Wrong — muscles can only **pull** by contracting, which is why they work in antagonistic pairs.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **List** four functions of the skeleton.
- *(Apply)* **Explain** the roles of tendons and ligaments.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why muscles must work in antagonistic pairs to move a joint.

---','{"concept":1,"the":17,"skeletal":1,"system":1,"and":9,"movement":3,"definition":1,"skeleton":2,"supports":1,"body":2,"protects":2,"organs":1,"allows":1,"makes":1,"blood":1,"cells":1,"major":1,"bones":6,"include":1,"skull":1,"brain":1,"ribs":1,"protect":2,"heart":1,"lungs":1,"spine":1,"vertebrae":1,"support":1,"spinal":1,"cord":1,"femur":1,"thigh":1,"largest":1,"bone":4,"humerus":1,"upper":1,"arm":2,"pelvis":1,"needs":1,"muscles":9,"tendons":3,"ligaments":3,"working":1,"together":1,"contract":1,"pull":5,"attach":2,"muscle":1,"joints":2,"work":4,"antagonistic":3,"pairs":4,"biceps":4,"triceps":4,"one":1,"contracts":5,"while":2,"other":1,"relaxes":3,"verbal":1,"diagram":1,"elbow":1,"front":1,"attaches":1,"tendon":1,"across":1,"joint":2,"when":1,"bends":1,"back":1,"straighten":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"lifting":1,"bag":1,"pulling":1,"forearm":1,"lowering":1,"analogy":1,"are":1,"like":1,"ropes":2,"levers":2,"that":1,"pivot":1,"why":4,"matters":1,"explains":1,"how":1,"moves":1,"must":2,"they":2,"can":3,"only":2,"not":1,"push":2,"misconception":1,"well":1,"wrong":1,"contracting":1,"which":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"list":1,"four":1,"functions":1,"apply":1,"explain":2,"roles":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"move":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_504772724237502941','file_a8bb6ddf9d5c59f486','biology.md','Concept: Joints','**Definition.** A **joint** is where two or more bones meet, allowing movement (or holding bones firmly). Three main types:
- **Hinge joint** (e.g. elbow, knee) — allows back-and-forth movement in one plane, like a door hinge.
- **Ball-and-socket joint** (e.g. shoulder, hip) — allows movement in many directions (rotation).
- **Fixed/immovable joint** (e.g. between skull bones) — no movement, provides protection.

Joints contain **cartilage** (cushions bone ends), **synovial fluid** (lubricates), and are held by **ligaments**.

**Verbal diagram.** A ball-and-socket: the rounded head of one bone (the "ball", e.g. femur) sits in a cup-shaped socket (e.g. pelvis), allowing wide rotation.

**Real-world example.** Your shoulder (ball-and-socket) can circle fully; your knee (hinge) mainly bends and straightens.

**Analogy.** A hinge joint is a door hinge; a ball-and-socket joint is a joystick that moves in all directions.

**Why it matters.** Different joints allow the range of movements the body needs while protecting bones.

**Misconception.** *"All joints allow movement."* Wrong — **fixed joints** (like those in the skull) do not move; they protect and provide structure.

**Command-term questions**
- *(Recall)* **Name** the three main types of joint with one example each.
- *(Apply)* **Identify** the joint type at the knee and describe its movement.
- *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Compare** how a hinge joint and a ball-and-socket joint differ in movement.

---
