('chunk_aa4623f457b4804c33','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Unit 1: Matter and its Composition','- **Key Concept**: Change
- **Related Concepts**: Form, Patterns, Evidence
- **Global Context**: Scientific and technical innovation (how humans separate, purify and use materials)
- **Statement of Inquiry**: The form and composition of matter determine how its parts can be identified and separated by physical and chemical means.
- **Inquiry Questions**:
  - *Factual*: What are elements, compounds and mixtures, and how do we separate mixtures?
  - *Conceptual*: How does the way particles are combined change the properties of a substance?
  - *Debatable*: Is any separated substance ever truly "pure"?','{"unit":1,"matter":2,"and":8,"its":2,"composition":2,"key":1,"concept":1,"change":2,"related":1,"concepts":1,"form":2,"patterns":1,"evidence":1,"global":1,"context":1,"scientific":1,"technical":1,"innovation":1,"how":4,"humans":1,"separate":2,"purify":1,"use":1,"materials":1,"statement":1,"inquiry":2,"the":3,"determine":1,"parts":1,"can":1,"identified":1,"separated":2,"physical":1,"chemical":1,"means":1,"questions":1,"factual":1,"what":1,"are":2,"elements":1,"compounds":1,"mixtures":2,"conceptual":1,"does":1,"way":1,"particles":1,"combined":1,"properties":1,"substance":2,"debatable":1,"any":1,"ever":1,"truly":1,"pure":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_f52dd8d691d41ded4a','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Concept: The Atom','- **Definition**: An atom is the smallest particle of an element that still has the properties of that element. It has a central **nucleus** (protons + neutrons) surrounded by **electrons**.
- **Real-world example**: A single copper atom is the smallest unit of copper in a copper wire.
- **Analogy**: An atom is like a tiny solar system — the dense nucleus is the "sun" and electrons orbit like "planets" (a simplified model).
- **Why it matters**: Everything is made of atoms; understanding them explains all chemical behaviour.
- **Subatomic particles**: protons (positive, in nucleus), neutrons (neutral, in nucleus), electrons (negative, around nucleus).
- **Misconception**: *"Atoms are solid balls with no empty space."* Believed because diagrams show shaded circles. Wrong because an atom is mostly empty space; the nucleus is tiny compared with the electron cloud. Corrective: if the atom were a stadium, the nucleus would be a pea at the centre.
- **IB questions**:
  1. (Recall) **State** the three subatomic particles found in an atom.
  2. (Apply) **Label** the nucleus and electrons on a diagram of a helium atom.
  3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Explain** why an atom is described as electrically neutral overall.','{"concept":1,"the":13,"atom":9,"definition":1,"smallest":2,"particle":1,"element":2,"that":2,"still":1,"has":2,"properties":1,"central":1,"nucleus":8,"protons":2,"neutrons":2,"surrounded":1,"electrons":4,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"single":1,"copper":3,"unit":1,"wire":1,"analogy":1,"like":2,"tiny":2,"solar":1,"system":1,"dense":1,"sun":1,"and":2,"orbit":1,"planets":1,"simplified":1,"model":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"everything":1,"made":1,"atoms":2,"understanding":1,"them":1,"explains":1,"all":1,"chemical":1,"behaviour":1,"subatomic":2,"particles":2,"positive":1,"neutral":2,"negative":1,"around":1,"misconception":1,"are":1,"solid":1,"balls":1,"with":2,"empty":2,"space":2,"believed":1,"because":2,"diagrams":1,"show":1,"shaded":1,"circles":1,"wrong":1,"mostly":1,"compared":1,"electron":1,"cloud":1,"corrective":1,"were":1,"stadium":1,"would":1,"pea":1,"centre":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"three":1,"found":1,"apply":1,"label":1,"diagram":1,"helium":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"described":1,"electrically":1,"overall":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_0ef83bcb6dfac1c847','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Concept: Elements','- **Definition**: An element is a pure substance made of only one type of atom; it cannot be broken down into simpler substances by chemical means.
- **Real-world example**: Oxygen, gold, carbon.
- **Analogy**: An element is like a single Lego brick of one shape and colour.
- **Why it matters**: Elements are the building blocks of every compound and mixture.
- **Misconception**: *"Air is an element."* Wrong — air is a mixture of several elements and compounds (N₂, O₂, CO₂, argon, water vapour). Corrective: an element contains only one kind of atom.
- **IB questions**:
  1. (Recall) **Define** the term element.
  2. (Apply) **Identify** two elements from this list: water, iron, salt, helium.
  3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Distinguish** between an element and a compound at the atomic level.','{"concept":1,"elements":4,"definition":1,"element":6,"pure":1,"substance":1,"made":1,"only":2,"one":3,"type":1,"atom":2,"cannot":1,"broken":1,"down":1,"into":1,"simpler":1,"substances":1,"chemical":1,"means":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"oxygen":1,"gold":1,"carbon":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"single":1,"lego":1,"brick":1,"shape":1,"and":4,"colour":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"are":1,"the":3,"building":1,"blocks":1,"every":1,"compound":2,"mixture":2,"misconception":1,"air":2,"wrong":1,"several":1,"compounds":1,"argon":1,"water":2,"vapour":1,"corrective":1,"contains":1,"kind":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"define":1,"term":1,"apply":1,"identify":1,"two":1,"from":1,"this":1,"list":1,"iron":1,"salt":1,"helium":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"distinguish":1,"between":1,"atomic":1,"level":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d53ac9297c44922b1b','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Concept: Compounds','- **Definition**: A compound is a pure substance formed when two or more different elements are chemically bonded in a fixed ratio.
- **Real-world example**: Water (H₂O) is hydrogen chemically bonded to oxygen; table salt (NaCl) is sodium bonded to chlorine.
- **Analogy**: A compound is like a baked cake — you cannot pick the flour back out because it has chemically changed.
- **Why it matters**: Most substances around us are compounds, not free elements.
- **Elements vs compounds at the atomic/molecular level**: an element''s smallest particle contains identical atoms; a compound''s smallest particle (a molecule or formula unit) contains different atoms bonded together in a set ratio.
- **Misconception**: *"A compound is just a mixture of its elements."* Wrong — in a compound the elements are chemically joined and lose their own properties; a mixture keeps them separate. Corrective: sodium (explosive metal) + chlorine (poison gas) → sodium chloride (edible salt).
- **IB questions**:
  1. (Recall) **State** the ratio of hydrogen to oxygen atoms in water.
  2. (Apply) **Classify** CO₂, He and NaCl as element or compound.
  3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Explain**, using sodium chloride, how a compound''s properties differ from those of its constituent elements.','{"concept":1,"compounds":3,"definition":1,"compound":7,"pure":1,"substance":1,"formed":1,"when":1,"two":1,"more":1,"different":2,"elements":6,"are":3,"chemically":4,"bonded":4,"fixed":1,"ratio":3,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"water":2,"hydrogen":2,"oxygen":2,"table":1,"salt":2,"nacl":2,"sodium":4,"chlorine":2,"analogy":1,"like":1,"baked":1,"cake":1,"you":1,"cannot":1,"pick":1,"the":4,"flour":1,"back":1,"out":1,"because":1,"has":1,"changed":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"most":1,"substances":1,"around":1,"not":1,"free":1,"atomic":1,"molecular":1,"level":1,"element":2,"smallest":2,"particle":2,"contains":2,"identical":1,"atoms":3,"molecule":1,"formula":1,"unit":1,"together":1,"set":1,"misconception":1,"just":1,"mixture":2,"its":2,"wrong":1,"joined":1,"and":2,"lose":1,"their":1,"own":1,"properties":2,"keeps":1,"them":1,"separate":1,"corrective":1,"explosive":1,"metal":1,"poison":1,"gas":1,"chloride":2,"edible":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"apply":1,"classify":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"using":1,"how":1,"differ":1,"from":1,"those":1,"constituent":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_8b76f67bc3323fe2c8','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Concept: Mixtures','- **Definition**: A mixture contains two or more substances physically combined but **not** chemically bonded; each keeps its own properties and can be present in any ratio.
- **Real-world example**: Sand and salt; air; sea water; a fruit salad.
- **Analogy**: A mixture is like a bag of mixed sweets — you can sort them back out one by one.
- **Why it matters**: Most raw materials in nature (crude oil, ores, air, sea water) are mixtures that must be separated.
- **Misconception**: *"Mixtures always have a fixed recipe."* Wrong — mixtures can be combined in any proportion; only compounds have a fixed ratio. Corrective: you can make salty water strong or weak; water is always exactly H₂O.','{"concept":1,"mixtures":4,"definition":1,"mixture":2,"contains":1,"two":1,"more":1,"substances":1,"physically":1,"combined":2,"but":1,"not":1,"chemically":1,"bonded":1,"each":1,"keeps":1,"its":1,"own":1,"properties":1,"and":2,"can":4,"present":1,"any":2,"ratio":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"sand":1,"salt":1,"air":2,"sea":2,"water":4,"fruit":1,"salad":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"bag":1,"mixed":1,"sweets":1,"you":2,"sort":1,"them":1,"back":1,"out":1,"one":2,"why":1,"matters":1,"most":1,"raw":1,"materials":1,"nature":1,"crude":1,"oil":1,"ores":1,"are":1,"that":1,"must":1,"separated":1,"misconception":1,"always":2,"have":2,"fixed":2,"recipe":1,"wrong":1,"proportion":1,"only":1,"compounds":1,"corrective":1,"make":1,"salty":1,"strong":1,"weak":1,"exactly":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_f6e2f855a52bc07cf2','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Concept: Compound vs Mixture Comparison','- Compound: elements chemically bonded; fixed ratio; new properties; separated only by chemical means; energy change on forming.
- Mixture: substances physically combined; any ratio; keep original properties; separated by physical means; little or no energy change on forming.
- **IB questions**:
  1. (Recall) **State** one difference between a compound and a mixture.
  2. (Apply) **Classify** each as element, compound or mixture: brass, oxygen, carbon dioxide, muddy water.
  3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Compare** how a compound and a mixture can be separated.','{"concept":1,"compound":5,"mixture":5,"comparison":1,"elements":1,"chemically":1,"bonded":1,"fixed":1,"ratio":2,"new":1,"properties":2,"separated":3,"only":1,"chemical":1,"means":2,"energy":2,"change":2,"forming":2,"substances":1,"physically":1,"combined":1,"any":1,"keep":1,"original":1,"physical":1,"little":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"one":1,"difference":1,"between":1,"and":2,"apply":1,"classify":1,"each":1,"element":1,"brass":1,"oxygen":1,"carbon":1,"dioxide":1,"muddy":1,"water":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"compare":1,"how":1,"can":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_04b5ccc46fc3fcfce3','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Concept: Classifying Substances','- **Definition**: Sorting a substance as element, compound or mixture using the number of atom types and whether they are bonded.
- **Worked example**: 
  - Diamond → one atom type (carbon), bonded → **element**.
  - Sugar (C₁₂H₂₂O₁₁) → several atom types, chemically bonded, fixed ratio → **compound**.
  - Tea → several substances, physically combined → **mixture**.','{"concept":1,"classifying":1,"substances":2,"definition":1,"sorting":1,"substance":1,"element":2,"compound":2,"mixture":2,"using":1,"the":1,"number":1,"atom":3,"types":2,"and":1,"whether":1,"they":1,"are":1,"bonded":3,"worked":1,"example":1,"diamond":1,"one":1,"type":1,"carbon":1,"sugar":1,"several":2,"chemically":1,"fixed":1,"ratio":1,"tea":1,"physically":1,"combined":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d2e33f956aad869b8e','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Concept: Separation Techniques','Physical methods separate the parts of a **mixture** without changing them chemically.

| Technique | Separates | Principle |
|-----------|-----------|-----------|
| Filtration | Insoluble solid from a liquid | Solid particles too big to pass through filter paper |
| Evaporation | Dissolved solid from solution | Liquid turns to vapour, solid left behind |
| Crystallization | Pure solid crystals from solution | Solubility falls as solution cools; crystals form |
| Distillation (simple) | Pure liquid (solvent) from solution | Liquid boils, vapour is cooled/condensed back to liquid |
| Fractional distillation | Two or more miscible liquids | Different boiling points; fractions collected at different temperatures |
| Sublimation | Solid that turns straight to gas (e.g. iodine, NH₄Cl) from a non-subliming solid | One solid sublimes on heating and re-solidifies elsewhere |
| Separating funnel | Two immiscible liquids (oil + water) | Different densities; lower layer run off through the tap |
| Chromatography | Coloured/soluble components of a solution | Different substances travel different distances with the solvent |

- **Real-world example**: A water treatment plant filters, then evaporates/distills to purify water; oil refineries use fractional distillation.
- **Analogy**: Separation is like sorting laundry — a sieve (filtration), a clothes line drying (evaporation), or sorting by weight.
- **Physical vs chemical separation**: Physical separation (all the above) uses differences in physical properties (size, boiling point, solubility, density) and gives back the original substances unchanged. **Chemical separation** breaks bonds in a compound (e.g. electrolysis of water into H₂ and O₂) and produces new substances.
- **Misconception**: *"Distillation removes all impurities from water forever."* Wrong — distillation separates dissolved solids but volatile substances with similar boiling points can carry over. Corrective: distillation separates by boiling point, not by "cleanliness".
- **IB questions**:
  1. (Recall) **State** the technique used to separate sand from water.
  2. (Apply) **Outline** how you would obtain pure water from salty water.
  3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Compare** physical and chemical methods of separation.

#### Practical Note — Separating a Salt/Sand Mixture
- **Method**: Add water, stir (salt dissolves). Filter → sand stays on filter paper. Evaporate the filtrate → salt crystals remain.
- **Variables**: Independent = amount of water added; Dependent = mass of salt recovered; Controlled = mass of starting mixture, temperature of evaporation.
- **Expected result**: Sand recovered on filter paper; white salt crystals from evaporation; combined mass ≈ starting mass (conservation of mass).','{"concept":1,"separation":6,"techniques":1,"physical":5,"methods":2,"separate":2,"the":7,"parts":1,"mixture":3,"without":1,"changing":1,"them":1,"chemically":1,"technique":2,"separates":3,"principle":1,"filtration":2,"insoluble":1,"solid":8,"from":9,"liquid":5,"particles":1,"too":1,"big":1,"pass":1,"through":2,"filter":4,"paper":3,"evaporation":4,"dissolved":2,"solution":5,"turns":2,"vapour":2,"left":1,"behind":1,"crystallization":1,"pure":3,"crystals":4,"solubility":2,"falls":1,"cools":1,"form":1,"distillation":6,"simple":1,"solvent":2,"boils":1,"cooled":1,"condensed":1,"back":2,"fractional":2,"two":2,"more":1,"miscible":1,"liquids":2,"different":5,"boiling":4,"points":2,"fractions":1,"collected":1,"temperatures":1,"sublimation":1,"that":1,"straight":1,"gas":1,"iodine":1,"non":1,"subliming":1,"one":1,"sublimes":1,"heating":1,"and":5,"solidifies":1,"elsewhere":1,"separating":2,"funnel":1,"immiscible":1,"oil":2,"water":10,"densities":1,"lower":1,"layer":1,"run":1,"off":1,"tap":1,"chromatography":1,"coloured":1,"soluble":1,"components":1,"substances":4,"travel":1,"distances":1,"with":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"treatment":1,"plant":1,"filters":1,"then":1,"evaporates":1,"distills":1,"purify":1,"refineries":1,"use":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"sorting":2,"laundry":1,"sieve":1,"clothes":1,"line":1,"drying":1,"weight":1,"chemical":3,"all":2,"above":1,"uses":1,"differences":1,"properties":1,"size":1,"point":2,"density":1,"gives":1,"original":1,"unchanged":1,"breaks":1,"bonds":1,"compound":1,"electrolysis":1,"into":1,"produces":1,"new":1,"misconception":1,"removes":1,"impurities":1,"forever":1,"wrong":1,"solids":1,"but":1,"volatile":1,"similar":1,"can":1,"carry":1,"over":1,"corrective":1,"not":1,"cleanliness":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"used":1,"sand":4,"apply":1,"outline":1,"how":1,"you":1,"would":1,"obtain":1,"salty":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"compare":1,"practical":1,"note":1,"salt":5,"method":1,"add":1,"stir":1,"dissolves":1,"stays":1,"evaporate":1,"filtrate":1,"remain":1,"variables":1,"independent":1,"amount":1,"added":1,"dependent":1,"mass":5,"recovered":2,"controlled":1,"starting":2,"temperature":1,"expected":1,"result":1,"white":1,"combined":1,"conservation":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_8948ff390de06ad979','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Concept: Paper Chromatography','- **Definition**: A technique that separates the dissolved components of a mixture based on how far each travels up a paper as a solvent moves through it.
- **Components**: 
  - **Stationary phase** — the chromatography paper.
  - **Mobile phase** — the solvent (water, ethanol) that moves up the paper.
  - **Baseline** — pencil line where the sample spot is placed.
  - **Solvent front** — the furthest point the solvent reaches.
- **Real-world example**: Testing which dyes make up a black felt-tip ink; forensic analysis of inks; checking food colourings.
- **Analogy**: A race — lighter, more soluble components "run" faster and further up the paper than heavier, less soluble ones.
- **Why it matters**: It identifies unknown substances and checks purity using tiny samples.','{"concept":1,"paper":5,"chromatography":2,"definition":1,"technique":1,"that":2,"separates":1,"the":8,"dissolved":1,"components":3,"mixture":1,"based":1,"how":1,"far":1,"each":1,"travels":1,"solvent":4,"moves":2,"through":1,"stationary":1,"phase":2,"mobile":1,"water":1,"ethanol":1,"baseline":1,"pencil":1,"line":1,"where":1,"sample":1,"spot":1,"placed":1,"front":1,"furthest":1,"point":1,"reaches":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"testing":1,"which":1,"dyes":1,"make":1,"black":1,"felt":1,"tip":1,"ink":1,"forensic":1,"analysis":1,"inks":1,"checking":1,"food":1,"colourings":1,"analogy":1,"race":1,"lighter":1,"more":1,"soluble":2,"run":1,"faster":1,"and":2,"further":1,"than":1,"heavier":1,"less":1,"ones":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"identifies":1,"unknown":1,"substances":1,"checks":1,"purity":1,"using":1,"tiny":1,"samples":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_6fba5a38ad554f477a','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Concept: Rf Value','- **Definition**: The retention factor, a ratio comparing how far a component moves to how far the solvent moves. It is a fixed value for a substance in a given solvent.
- **Formula**: 
```
Rf = distance moved by substance / distance moved by solvent
```
- **Worked example**: A spot moves 4.0 cm; the solvent front moves 8.0 cm. 
```
Rf = 4.0 / 8.0 = 0.5
```
Rf has no units and is always between 0 and 1. An unknown with the same Rf as a known reference (run in the same conditions) is likely the same substance.
- **Misconception**: *"Rf can be greater than 1."* Wrong — a component can never travel further than the solvent front, so Rf ≤ 1. Corrective: if you calculate Rf > 1 you have swapped the numbers.
- **IB questions**:
  1. (Recall) **State** the formula for Rf value.
  2. (Apply) **Calculate** the Rf of a pigment that moves 3 cm when the solvent moves 12 cm.
  3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Explain** how Rf values can be used to identify an unknown pigment in a mixture.

#### Practical Note — Paper Chromatography of Ink
- **Method**: Draw a **pencil** baseline 2 cm from the bottom of the paper. Place a small spot of ink on the line. Stand the paper in a beaker with solvent below the baseline. Let the solvent rise, remove before it reaches the top, mark the solvent front, let dry.
- **Variables**: Independent = the ink sample; Dependent = distance each colour travels (Rf); Controlled = solvent, paper type, temperature, spot size.
- **Expected result**: The single spot separates into several coloured spots; each has a characteristic Rf.
- **Why pencil?** Pencil (graphite) is insoluble and does not run in the solvent; pen ink would separate too.','{"concept":1,"value":3,"definition":1,"the":22,"retention":1,"factor":1,"ratio":1,"comparing":1,"how":3,"far":2,"component":2,"moves":6,"solvent":11,"fixed":1,"for":2,"substance":3,"given":1,"formula":2,"distance":3,"moved":2,"worked":1,"example":1,"spot":4,"front":3,"has":2,"units":1,"and":3,"always":1,"between":1,"unknown":2,"with":2,"same":3,"known":1,"reference":1,"run":2,"conditions":1,"likely":1,"misconception":1,"can":3,"greater":1,"than":2,"wrong":1,"never":1,"travel":1,"further":1,"corrective":1,"you":2,"calculate":2,"have":1,"swapped":1,"numbers":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"apply":1,"pigment":2,"that":1,"when":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"values":1,"used":1,"identify":1,"mixture":1,"practical":1,"note":1,"paper":4,"chromatography":1,"ink":4,"method":1,"draw":1,"pencil":3,"baseline":2,"from":1,"bottom":1,"place":1,"small":1,"line":1,"stand":1,"beaker":1,"below":1,"let":2,"rise":1,"remove":1,"before":1,"reaches":1,"top":1,"mark":1,"dry":1,"variables":1,"independent":1,"sample":1,"dependent":1,"each":2,"colour":1,"travels":1,"controlled":1,"type":1,"temperature":1,"size":1,"expected":1,"result":1,"single":1,"separates":1,"into":1,"several":1,"coloured":1,"spots":1,"characteristic":1,"why":1,"graphite":1,"insoluble":1,"does":1,"not":1,"pen":1,"would":1,"separate":1,"too":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d1f5d9bee2a4233266','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Concept: Choosing and Evaluating a Separation Process','- **Definition**: Selecting the best sequence of techniques to separate a given mixture based on the properties of its components, then judging how well it worked.
- **Real-world example**: To separate a mixture of sand, salt and iron filings: use a **magnet** (removes iron), add water and **filter** (removes sand), then **evaporate** (recovers salt).
- **Analogy**: Like planning a route with several stops in the right order.
- **Why it matters**: Real industries (mining, water treatment, pharmaceuticals) chain techniques to purify products.
- **Analysing effectiveness**: judge by purity of product, percentage recovered, time and energy used, and safety.
- **IB questions**:
  1. (Recall) **List** three properties used to choose a separation technique.
  2. (Apply) **Design** a process to separate a mixture of iron filings, sand and salt.
  3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Evaluate** the effectiveness of your process, suggesting one improvement.

